00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:35.330
So please join me in
welcoming Yvonne Pendleton.

00:00:40.624 --> 00:00:42.040
YVONNE PENDLETON:
It's my pleasure

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:45.390
to bring you news from your
next door neighbor at NASA Ames

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:49.700
Research Center about what we're
doing in the virtual world.

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:53.200
So the exact title
of our institute,

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:57.650
which we call SERVI for
short, is, as you just heard,

00:00:57.650 --> 00:01:01.710
Solar System Exploration
Research Virtual institute.

00:01:01.710 --> 00:01:03.740
And it's that last
part, virtual Institute,

00:01:03.740 --> 00:01:05.820
that really makes us
different from a number

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:10.060
of other activities and things
that you might hear about.

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:13.420
So I'm going to
go on in a second,

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:17.010
but I'm want to first introduce
to you two of our staff members

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:18.900
that I brought with me today.

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.030
We have a small
central office located

00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:23.080
at NASA Ames that
helps coordinate

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:25.940
the activities of the
hundreds of researchers

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:28.440
that we have distributed
across the country.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:31.270
And with me today, I have our
staff scientist Brad Bailey

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:33.350
who's here in the
audience, and also

00:01:33.350 --> 00:01:36.130
Brian Day who's our
director of communications

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:37.630
and public engagement.

00:01:37.630 --> 00:01:40.290
So when it comes
time for questions,

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:43.150
if you have any
questions that pertain

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:45.910
to either the
activities of our teams,

00:01:45.910 --> 00:01:48.010
or the outreach that
we do, they will

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:50.990
be able to help me
answer and go deeper.

00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:54.870
OK, so let me just
start by asking,

00:01:54.870 --> 00:01:56.640
what is a virtual Institute?

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.490
For some of you, you may not
have heard this term before.

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:00.970
Or for those of
you who have, you

00:02:00.970 --> 00:02:02.530
may have a different
idea from what

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:05.190
it is that we
actually do at SERVI.

00:02:05.190 --> 00:02:08.900
So in our idea, a
virtual Institute

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:11.820
is a distributed
organization that

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:16.200
allows you to pick the very
best investigations, teams

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:19.250
and facilities from
wherever they are.

00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:23.100
You don't have to be restricted
by geographical location

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:26.210
for somebody who has a certain
type of laboratory working

00:02:26.210 --> 00:02:27.890
with another group
that might have

00:02:27.890 --> 00:02:32.160
more expertise in
some other area.

00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:38.340
And by sharing the students,
and the facilities,

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:41.100
and the resources that
the various teams bring

00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:43.350
to the organization,
you can actually

00:02:43.350 --> 00:02:46.690
build a stronger
institute, I maintain,

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:49.800
than if you just had a
traditional bricks and mortar

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:51.850
building.

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:54.600
So I think you get more
bang for your buck.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:58.030
The small office that we have
that NASA Ames Research Center

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:01.950
is able to coordinate and
help the collaboration,

00:03:01.950 --> 00:03:04.900
both within the teams and
across the team lines.

00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:10.120
And we're able to do this
across a very interdisciplinary

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:11.340
subject area.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:14.230
And I'll tell you more about our
subject area in just a minute.

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:15.896
But first, I want to
tell you that there

00:03:15.896 --> 00:03:18.940
is a history of virtual
institutes at Ames.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:23.000
NASA has started the NASA
Astrobiology Institute,

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.770
which began in 1998 at Ames.

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:27.550
It's still going very strong.

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:32.650
And then in 2008, the NASA Lunar
Science Institute was born.

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:35.770
That is actually the
predecessor for SERVI,

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:38.180
and we have taken our
studies of the Moon

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:42.110
and expanded them now to include
studies also of near Earth

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:46.200
asteroids, and
the moons of Mars.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:49.200
Then, we also have to NASA
Aeronautics Research Institute,

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:51.560
which began in 2012.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:55.740
And SERVI was just born
last year, well in 2013,

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:59.350
a little over a year ago now.

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:02.480
OK, so this diagram,
this drawing,

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:07.750
is indicating the orbits of most
of the near Earth asteroids.

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:09.340
I say most because
we think we have

00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:11.400
found most of the large ones.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.390
But there are probably still a
few that we don't know about.

00:04:14.390 --> 00:04:18.149
And when you see that
kind of involvement

00:04:18.149 --> 00:04:21.320
of where they are located
relative to the Earth,

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:23.990
I think it becomes obvious
why NASA felt the need

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:28.100
to expand our purview to go
beyond studies of the Moon.

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:30.980
And that's why we now
include, as it says here,

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:33.830
the near Earth
asteroids, and also

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:35.560
the moons of Mars,
which we believe

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:39.250
may have been captured
asteroids themselves.

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:43.580
This institute is funded jointly
by both the Science Mission

00:04:43.580 --> 00:04:46.920
Directorate at NASA
headquarters in Washington, DC,

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:51.330
but also the human exploration
side what NASA does.

00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:53.600
And so, this is a
very important bridge

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:57.220
to join together science
and exploration so that you

00:04:57.220 --> 00:04:59.150
are addressing the
science questions you

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:01.250
need to know before you go.

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:04.650
So before we take humans
anywhere beyond low Earth orbit

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:07.480
again, there are certain
questions we want to address.

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:12.350
And our teams are looking at
what those conditions might

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:17.070
be that will help us get
there, and get there safely.

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:21.000
So in more detail what
does SERVI actually study?

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.370
Well, we have a long
list of items here,

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:28.320
but the role of
the Moon is still

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:30.350
very important to what we do.

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:33.770
We study the origin,
the composition,

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:36.300
the dynamics of all
of these bodies.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:39.210
So we'd like to know,
in particular, what kind

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:43.310
of questions cover
multiple bodies.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:46.070
In other words, if you
were interested in the dust

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:48.740
or the regolith that sits
on the Moon's surface,

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:50.960
you might have some of
the very same questions

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:54.630
that apply to the moons
of Mars, Phobos and Deimos

00:05:54.630 --> 00:05:57.060
and similarly to asteroids.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:06:00.810
And by understanding the
composition of these materials,

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:04.270
you would better be able
to design both vehicles

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:09.130
and environments for humans to
live in on any of those bodies,

00:06:09.130 --> 00:06:12.770
or even just to go there
for a short time to work.

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:13.740
Volatiles.

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:15.990
In its broadest sense,
these are materials

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:20.600
that may be able to be
liberated up from the surface,

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:23.140
or ice from down deep
inside of a crater.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:25.100
Those are very
important to us as well.

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:28.650
And they cover, again, the
multitude of the bodies

00:06:28.650 --> 00:06:30.120
that we study.

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:33.820
And you can read down this list
a number of the other areas

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.850
that SERVI is concerned with.

00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:39.040
So we put out a proposal
a little over a year

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.050
ago for teams to reply to.

00:06:43.050 --> 00:06:46.700
And from that, we
selected nine teams.

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:49.360
And here are the
principal investigators

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:53.520
that make up the current
composition of the SERVI

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.270
Institute teams.

00:06:55.270 --> 00:07:01.080
And you can see that the
principal investigators, just

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:03.160
in alphabetical
order here, I've got

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:07.160
to Bill Bottke who is from the
Southwest Research Institute,

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:11.840
and Dan Britt, who is from the
University of Central Florida.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:14.170
Ben Bussey from the
Applied Physics Laboratory

