00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:14.740
Or maybe not.

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:17.110
They themselves would
have a distribution

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:18.370
across the country.

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:23.802
And all of our teams communicate
using the virtual technology

00:08:23.802 --> 00:08:25.990
that I'll tell you a little
bit about in a minute.

00:08:25.990 --> 00:08:29.070
And we get together once
in a while in person,

00:08:29.070 --> 00:08:35.190
but by and large these are
virtual communications.

00:08:35.190 --> 00:08:38.260
OK, we also have eight
international partners.

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:40.340
Why would international
partners care

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:45.160
about joining a domestic
group like NASA's SERVI?

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:49.200
Well it turns out, through a
no exchange of funds basis,

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.200
if they become a
partner with us,

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:54.030
it facilitates their
getting the resources

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:57.030
within their own
country to develop

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:58.730
whatever kind of
program they wanted

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:01.370
to develop that's
relevant to what we do.

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:03.450
Perhaps it's
investigating the Moon.

00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:05.680
Or in the case of
Korea, they're very

00:09:05.680 --> 00:09:09.240
interested in going to the
Moon with a mission themselves.

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:12.180
Whatever the
country interest is,

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:15.410
if it relates to what we
do with our domestic teams,

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:18.330
we are happy to entertain
a proposal from them.

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:19.940
And so far eight
of them have been

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:23.200
accepted into our
international family.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:25.340
And then we urge
cross collaboration

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:28.750
between the domestic teams
and international partners.

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:31.460
And that's going really well.

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:35.110
This is a distribution of where
the principal investigators

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:39.140
and the co-investigators are
just for the domestic teams.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:40.830
And again, just to
give you an idea

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:45.020
that there are a total
of 318 researchers,

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:46.100
including the students.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.920
There are many students that
are involved with these teams.

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:52.640
And the average team
size is roughly 30.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:57.160
We have one that's
up to 60 in number.

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:00.160
OK, so getting down to
more details about what

00:10:00.160 --> 00:10:02.630
these teams actually
do, I've selected

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:04.260
just a few research highlights.

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:05.270
They have many.

00:10:05.270 --> 00:10:08.000
I mean each one of
these teams could easily

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:09.990
take up an entire
hour just to tell you

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:11.610
the fascinating
work they're doing.

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:13.650
But let me just give
you a few highlights.

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:16.270
So Dan Britt at the
University of Central Florida

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:19.680
has a team called the Center
for Lunar and Asteroid Surface

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:21.080
Science.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:23.190
And they study the
physical properties

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:25.170
of regoliths, the
dust that we've

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:27.990
talked about on the surface
of bodies like the Moon,

00:10:27.990 --> 00:10:30.710
but also asteroids
and the moons of Mars.

00:10:30.710 --> 00:10:34.150
The geotechnical properties,
the micro gravity effects

00:10:34.150 --> 00:10:40.810
that you might encounter, impact
ejecta dynamics, hydration,

00:10:40.810 --> 00:10:43.390
and weathering of the
near Earth asteroids.

00:10:43.390 --> 00:10:46.600
Over time, the four-and-a-half
billion years that these bodies

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:49.010
have been in space, there's
been a lot of weathering

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:49.900
that's happened.

00:10:49.900 --> 00:10:52.060
And the charging
and mobilization

00:10:52.060 --> 00:10:54.350
of dust on the surface
of any of these

00:10:54.350 --> 00:10:57.330
is going to affect any machinery
you're going to put there,

00:10:57.330 --> 00:11:02.140
and certainly the
astronauts themselves.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:04.320
So then, the next
one, Andy Rivkin,

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:09.110
the Applied Physics Laboratory
at Johns Hopkins University.

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:11.940
Their team is called
VORTICES, a very long name,

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:14.410
and NASA loves its acronyms.

00:11:14.410 --> 00:11:17.617
So you can see how they
developed VORTICES out

00:11:17.617 --> 00:11:18.200
of their name.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:20.340
But they study
volatiles, regolith,

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:23.050
and thermal investigations.

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:25.800
They look at the sources,
sinks and processes

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:30.780
and the interaction
that various materials

00:11:30.780 --> 00:11:33.420
will have with the
regoliths, and the evolution

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:38.250
of that dust on all
of the target bodies.

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:41.940
OK, the group at the
Goddard Space Flight Center,

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:45.610
led by Bill Farrell, this is
called the Dream Two Team.

00:11:45.610 --> 00:11:47.280
And the reason it's
called Dream Two

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:51.380
is because Dream One was part
of the NASA Lunar Science

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:55.630
Institute, which I was also the
director of in the last couple

00:11:55.630 --> 00:11:58.370
of years before it
transitioned into SERVI.

00:11:58.370 --> 00:12:01.030
So I got to know the teams
from the NASA Lunar Science

00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:02.510
Institute pretty well.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:06.310
And I was really pleased that
when we had our peer review

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:09.130
process of the
proposals, it turned out

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:11.410
several of the principal
investigators who

00:12:11.410 --> 00:12:14.420
had been leading teams under
the Lunar Science Institute

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:16.820
were selected for SERVI.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.880
So Bill Farrell
was one of those.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:21.140
And the dynamic
responsive environments

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:24.040
at asteroids, the Moon,
and the moons of Mars

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:26.310
is what he calls Dream Two.

00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:29.780
They study plasmas,
the plasma interaction

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:31.140
that comes from the solar wind.

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:32.850
When the solar wind
comes and interacts

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:35.520
with a body like
the Moon, it does

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:37.360
a number of interesting things.

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:41.920
And the fact that we now
see OH all over the surface

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:45.240
of the Moon, and the solar
wind contains hydrogen

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:50.500
as it's traveling and runs
into the regolith on the Moon,

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:52.360
you can see how the
H and the OH can

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:54.040
get together and form water.

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:58.000
So the plasma processes, as
they interact with the Moon

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.570
and the other bodies,
are very important.

00:13:00.570 --> 00:13:03.590
And you can also
see here that we

00:13:03.590 --> 00:13:07.895
have the solar wind
charging of asteroids.

00:13:07.895 --> 00:13:09.520
This is something
else that they study.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:10.350
They model this.

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:14.420
We have a lot of
interesting results

00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:16.900
that show the kinds
of things that you

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:20.120
need to think about when
you're looking at the charging

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:22.930
from these kinds
of interactions.

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:27.000
Timothy Glotch from
Stony Brook University

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.160
has a team that they
called The Rise Team.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:36.660
And they do the remote
sensing of airless bodies.

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:40.150
Field operations and metrics
for human exploration,

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:44.080
they look at the reactivity
and the toxicity of regoliths.

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:45.750
These can be
dangerous to humans.

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:48.140
So you know, when the
astronauts were on the Moon,

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:51.650
the spacesuits were
just covered with dust.

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:55.130
And getting back
into the vehicle,

00:13:55.130 --> 00:13:58.990
this is a concern, because if
you're breathing in that dust,

00:13:58.990 --> 00:14:03.530
it turned out it was a very
sharp, jagged kind of material.

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:05.420
And it can be really,
really harmful

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:06.810
over the long period of time.

00:14:06.810 --> 00:14:09.580
So they look at that
and try and understand

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:11.900
what we have to
mitigate against.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:14.830
They also do synchrotron
analyses of samples.

00:14:14.830 --> 00:14:18.780
And they look at volcanics
and impact crater analogue

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:19.350
research.

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:22.580
Which means you go to places on
the Earth that look like good

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:24.790
analogues for places
you want to go in space,

00:14:24.790 --> 00:14:27.290
and you try out some
your machinery and some

00:14:27.290 --> 00:14:32.590
of your techniques to see
how they would best work.

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:34.840
OK, continuing on
Mihaly Horanyia

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:39.630
from the University of
Colorado, his Institute team,

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:43.900
called Impact, has developed
the world's fastest dust

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:45.080
accelerator.

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:49.090
And this is open to the
entire scientific community

00:14:49.090 --> 00:14:52.710
and exploration community, so
that people can take samples

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:53.430
there.

00:14:53.430 --> 00:14:56.980
They can try out
new experiments.

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:58.990
And it's really going well.

00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:01.960
They're doing a lot
of phenomenal work.

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:05.320
And they have just
built a new ion

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:08.410
gun that simulates the
solar wind so that they

00:15:08.410 --> 00:15:12.070
can extend this
research even further.

00:15:12.070 --> 00:15:16.200
And here you can see the
penetration and the charging

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:19.610
studies that they do as well.

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:23.860
Carle Pieters from Brown
University, her team

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:26.645
does a lot of interesting
stuff with the evolution

00:15:26.645 --> 00:15:30.440
and environment of
whatever destination

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:31.810
we're going to go to.

00:15:31.810 --> 00:15:34.600
But I'd like to really
highlight the work that they've

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:37.380
done on the Moon,
because I think

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:39.650
one of the most exciting
results that we've learned

00:15:39.650 --> 00:15:42.990
about the Moon is the
fact that it's so wet.

00:15:42.990 --> 00:15:46.410
Now, it's wet compared to
what we thought it was.

00:15:46.410 --> 00:15:50.130
It was so dry a few years ago.

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:52.260
I mean we thought
it was very dry.

00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:55.590
And it's maybe about as
wet as the Sahara Desert.

00:15:55.590 --> 00:15:58.540
But that's still lot wetter
than that what we thought.

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:03.760
So to put it all in
perspective, but the water

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:06.850
is in very different locations.

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:10.030
And that indicates it came
from probably at least

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:13.020
three sources, three
different sources.

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:15.772
And the one that we
found inside the crater

00:16:15.772 --> 00:16:17.980
when we had the LCROSS
mission-- I'm sure many of you

00:16:17.980 --> 00:16:20.690
would remember that a
few years ago in 2009.

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:22.530
This was a mission
that went to the Moon,

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:24.570
deliberately crashed
into a crater,

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:26.920
kicked up, excavated
a bunch of material,

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:30.060
and then studied what
the composition was.

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:34.190
The LCROSS mission, which
was developed at Ames,

00:16:34.190 --> 00:16:36.440
revealed that we have
water ice in the bottom

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:39.100
of a crater, the Cabeus crater.

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:41.750
Well, that was
great confirmation.

00:16:41.750 --> 00:16:43.670
We were all very
excited about it.

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:46.220
But frankly, I wasn't
all that surprised.

00:16:46.220 --> 00:16:47.963
I kind of thought
there would be ice down

00:16:47.963 --> 00:16:49.560
in the bottom of a crater.

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:52.060
What I didn't expect
was that we have

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:56.740
water in the rocks that came
up from deep inside the Moon

00:16:56.740 --> 00:16:58.260
that the astronauts picked up.

00:16:58.260 --> 00:17:01.040
In the Apollo samples, it
turns out some of those samples

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:04.859
that they brought back contained
glass beads, volcanic glass

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:07.750
beads that could protect
the water inside it.

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:11.079
And now, all these years
later, we have the technology,

00:17:11.079 --> 00:17:14.339
we have the instruments to go
back and analyze those samples

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:16.359
in greater depth
and differently.

00:17:16.359 --> 00:17:19.780
And that's where we found
quite a bit more water

00:17:19.780 --> 00:17:21.270
than we previously thought.

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:23.010
And then, the third
component of water I

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:28.770
already mentioned to you, which
is the OH that exists literally

00:17:28.770 --> 00:17:31.800
across the Moon in very
different terrains.

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:33.630
And the interesting
thing about that

00:17:33.630 --> 00:17:38.250
is that it seems to be
replenished on a current cycle.

00:17:38.250 --> 00:17:41.610
This isn't just water that
was deposited a long time ago,

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:47.090
like deep in the crater that
happened a long time ago,

00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:49.030
and that's that,
and this is now.

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:52.170
We think we're seeing
actual replenishment

00:17:52.170 --> 00:17:54.835
in these different
scenarios, and not

00:17:54.835 --> 00:17:56.210
the water deep in
the Moon coming

00:17:56.210 --> 00:17:57.710
up, but of the one
on the surface,

00:17:57.710 --> 00:17:59.420
and also some of the craters.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:02.660
And that's fascinating
to me, because that just

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:04.820
changes a lot of
the physics of what

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:06.890
we thought was
happening on the Moon.

00:18:06.890 --> 00:18:09.640
And if we understand how
it's happening on the Moon,

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:11.265
we then understand
more about how

00:18:11.265 --> 00:18:15.940
it could happen on Phobos
and Deimos, and other bodies,

00:18:15.940 --> 00:18:19.810
and near Earth asteroids
that we might go to.

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:23.880
OK, so going on to a couple more
of our teams, Bill Bottke, who

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:27.940
runs a very interesting team
out of the Southwest Research

00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:30.740
Institute in Boulder,
Colorado, they

00:18:30.740 --> 00:18:33.470
do a lot of theoretical
modeling where

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:36.430
they look at the dynamics
and the formation

00:18:36.430 --> 00:18:38.110
of the early solar system.

00:18:38.110 --> 00:18:39.730
In fact, in just
about a week I'm

00:18:39.730 --> 00:18:41.220
going to be at a conference.

00:18:41.220 --> 00:18:45.380
It's all about early
bombardment of the solar system.

00:18:45.380 --> 00:18:48.940
And they'll be talking
about what happened when.

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:52.020
What big bodies hit
the Earth and the Moon,

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:54.280
what they did,
when they hit, how

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:56.770
they affected the other
terrestrial planets.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:18:58.810
And computer models
can really tell us

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:01.790
a lot about how all
of this happened.

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:04.680
The migration of planets
from the early part

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:09.350
of the solar system to today has
a lot to do with the dynamics

00:19:09.350 --> 00:19:11.950
that these bodies
found themselves on,

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:15.460
the trajectories and
that sort of thing.

00:19:15.460 --> 00:19:17.920
He also looks at things
like how asteroids

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:20.570
could be stuck together, or
how easily you could pull them

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:21.320
apart.

00:19:21.320 --> 00:19:25.950
One of the concerns we have with
asteroids is that some of them

00:19:25.950 --> 00:19:28.516
seem to be extremely fragile.

00:19:28.516 --> 00:19:30.640
And you don't want to have
a mission to an asteroid

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:32.560
that you go up to, and
as soon as you touch it,

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:33.640
the whole thing falls apart.

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:35.473
And now, you've got a
whole bunch of little,

00:19:35.473 --> 00:19:37.400
or maybe not so little, pieces.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:40.240
And the models that
we have are helping us

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:43.270
understand how that works.

00:19:43.270 --> 00:19:46.270
Jennifer Heldmann at
Ames Research Center

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:51.640
is leading a team that she calls
FINESSE, a very nice acronym.

00:19:51.640 --> 00:19:57.360
And what she's doing is looking
again into the Earth analogues

00:19:57.360 --> 00:19:59.630
that I mentioned just
a little while ago,

00:19:59.630 --> 00:20:02.000
so that you can really
understand what you should do

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.080
when, if you were out exploring,
both with humans and with

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:07.850
machines.

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:12.560
So for instance, their team
went to a couple of places

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:14.710
in this past year.

00:20:14.710 --> 00:20:17.440
And the one that I'd like to
tell you about is in Idaho.

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:18.790
It's called Craters of the Moon.

00:20:18.790 --> 00:20:21.610
Maybe some of you have been
to this national monument.

00:20:21.610 --> 00:20:27.230
And they looked at the way
you would operate machinery

00:20:27.230 --> 00:20:30.710
from a distance, simulating
what it would be like

00:20:30.710 --> 00:20:34.020
if you had a back science
room here on Earth trying

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:38.840
to run something on the
Moon, or on an asteroid.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:44.140
And so, they did take quite a
bit building in the time delay

00:20:44.140 --> 00:20:46.170
that you'd have
in communications,

00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:48.825
things like that.

00:20:48.825 --> 00:20:52.430
Let's see, and the
last team that I'm want

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:55.280
to mention here, David Kring
from the Lunar and Planetary

00:20:55.280 --> 00:20:57.910
Institute in Houston.

00:20:57.910 --> 00:21:01.670
They study the inner solar
system impact processes.

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.640
And you'll see a
similarity in themes

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:05.174
in all the things
I'm saying here.

00:21:05.174 --> 00:21:06.840
It's probably kind
of blending together,

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:08.050
like which one does what?

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:08.890
Well, you know what?

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:10.500
That's exactly the purpose.

00:21:10.500 --> 00:21:12.310
We want them to blend together.

00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:15.150
We want to not see
the lines between what

00:21:15.150 --> 00:21:17.790
these different teams
do, because I believe

00:21:17.790 --> 00:21:20.590
it's by the collaboration
and the crossover,

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:22.460
what these teams
bring to the table,

00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:26.200
that new science gets developed,
new directions are found.

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:29.140
And this is where the
most creative discoveries

00:21:29.140 --> 00:21:31.040
seem to be happening.

00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:33.360
So what David does is
he looks at the impact

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:37.360
history and processes, the
geochemistry of the regoliths,

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:40.470
and age dating of
regolith materials.

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:43.660
He looks at the near Earth
asteroid identification

00:21:43.660 --> 00:21:45.160
and characterization.

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:49.510
And he also works a lot with
the next generation training

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:53.000
of both the young people that
will go into these fields,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.150
and also astronauts, the
new classes of astronauts,

00:21:56.150 --> 00:22:01.200
so that they know how to
identify rocks and the geology

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:03.080
side of what astronauts
need to know,

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.820
as well as a few other things.

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:08.130
And some of the things
that his team has just

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:12.740
recently finished, they did
a global lunar landing site

00:22:12.740 --> 00:22:15.500
database that is now
open and available

00:22:15.500 --> 00:22:17.220
for the entire community.

00:22:17.220 --> 00:22:24.360
So these teams are creating
materials that are available

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:26.740
not just for the
teams themselves

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:29.220
but to the entire science
and exploration community.

00:22:31.930 --> 00:22:35.550
OK, so another thing that we do
it within the virtual Institute

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:39.610
that I really like a lot is
we build and share facilities.

00:22:39.610 --> 00:22:42.590
And this first picture
that we have here

00:22:42.590 --> 00:22:45.150
is about the dust
accelerator that I

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:47.800
mentioned at the
University of Colorado.

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:50.750
And that was up and
running, actually,

00:22:50.750 --> 00:22:52.850
during the Lunar
Science Institute,

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:55.140
because, again,
Mihaly Horanyia was

00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:57.720
one of the principal
investigators who

00:22:57.720 --> 00:23:00.630
led a team under the Lunar
Science Institute that is now

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:03.270
part of SERVI.

00:23:03.270 --> 00:23:06.840
And at Brown University
there's something called RELAB.

00:23:06.840 --> 00:23:10.750
This is a spectroscopy lab
where they look at samples

00:23:10.750 --> 00:23:12.910
and help people
analyze and understand

00:23:12.910 --> 00:23:16.270
what their field
samples are made of,

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:19.220
and the new components
that they make as well.

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:21.260
And at Brown
University, they've also

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:25.210
developed something that is a
3D immersive environment, which

00:23:25.210 --> 00:23:27.620
is something that I think
the Google folks would

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:29.540
be especially interested in.

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:31.100
So that you feel
like you're there,

00:23:31.100 --> 00:23:32.840
and you look around
in all directions,

00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:35.840
and it's just like
you're really there.

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:38.880
This was modeled
after what we call

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:41.030
the KeckCAVES, which
are at UC Davis.

00:23:41.030 --> 00:23:43.430
Maybe some of you are
familiar with that.

00:23:43.430 --> 00:23:46.070
But they have the
same kind of facility

00:23:46.070 --> 00:23:48.398
now at Brown University.

00:23:48.398 --> 00:23:50.394
OK.

00:23:50.394 --> 00:23:51.392
Oh, wait a minute.

00:23:51.392 --> 00:23:52.390
OK.

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:54.720
And at Ames we have a
couple of facilities

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:56.000
that we share as well.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:57.640
There's a regolith
test bed where

00:23:57.640 --> 00:24:01.600
we have eight tons of
simulant of lunar material.

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:06.000
And we have little rovers
that run around in this yard.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.970
I use it with students remotely.

00:24:08.970 --> 00:24:12.920
They can be across the world,
and they can operate the Rover.

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:14.990
And we've built
in little lessons

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:17.310
where they can go up
and try and identify

00:24:17.310 --> 00:24:19.750
the difference between
a meteorite and a rock,

00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:23.470
and take pictures of
it, that sort of thing.

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:27.700
There are scientific uses
for the test bed as well.

00:24:27.700 --> 00:24:29.870
And at Stony Brook
University, there

00:24:29.870 --> 00:24:32.880
is a vibrational
spectroscopy lab.

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:34.640
And this is, again,
something where

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:37.720
people would bring
their samples to it

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:41.205
and try and understand-- or
something that they built

00:24:41.205 --> 00:24:43.740
or created-- and try to
understand more about how

00:24:43.740 --> 00:24:45.540
it would interact
with or be interacted

00:24:45.540 --> 00:24:52.130
on by some sort of process,
and also what it's made out of.

00:24:52.130 --> 00:24:55.377
OK, another part
I wanted to stress

00:24:55.377 --> 00:24:57.700
is the SERVI team
collaborations that we

00:24:57.700 --> 00:24:59.580
have across the team lines.

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:02.270
And so just a
couple of examples.

00:25:02.270 --> 00:25:07.560
This one, this first one,
came about in the very first

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:10.190
experience where we brought
the principal investigators

00:25:10.190 --> 00:25:12.320
together to meet
for the first time.

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:15.270
And over this two-day period
where they met face-to-face,

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:17.700
we were a NASA
Ames, we asked them

00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:20.180
to please come up
with a list of areas

00:25:20.180 --> 00:25:23.932
where they thought their
area could cross over

00:25:23.932 --> 00:25:25.390
and they could find
a collaboration

00:25:25.390 --> 00:25:26.556
with one of the other teams.

00:25:26.556 --> 00:25:29.030
We had each of the teams
give a little synopsis

00:25:29.030 --> 00:25:30.610
of what their proposal was.

00:25:30.610 --> 00:25:32.750
Now, keep in mind,
these were teams

00:25:32.750 --> 00:25:35.100
that were competitors
just moments ago.

00:25:35.100 --> 00:25:37.890
And now, we're asking
them to share everything.

00:25:37.890 --> 00:25:40.060
Share your data,
share your processes,

00:25:40.060 --> 00:25:42.200
tell us what you're
going to do, and look

00:25:42.200 --> 00:25:45.230
for ways-- trust each other and
look for ways to work together.

00:25:45.230 --> 00:25:47.260
And they did it instantly.

00:25:47.260 --> 00:25:49.050
And one of the ideas
that came out of it

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:51.780
was to have this
sample repository

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:56.090
at the Natural
History Museum, where

00:25:56.090 --> 00:25:59.210
any team that collects
any kind of field sample,

00:25:59.210 --> 00:26:02.810
or had a sample that they
made, could bring it together

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:06.180
and put it in one place,
so that if you wanted

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:08.500
to do some sort
of process on it,

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:11.700
you could know that you
were using the same rock.

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:14.570
Two different teams doing
two different processes

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:17.640
on the same sample
is a lot better

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:20.680
than using two entirely
different samples that you just

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:23.800
happen to think are the same
rock, or the same material.

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:27.550
And this one ran into just
a little bit of a hiccup,

00:26:27.550 --> 00:26:30.360
because it turns out the
Natural History Museum does not

00:26:30.360 --> 00:26:34.250
take samples that
are found on Earth.

00:26:34.250 --> 00:26:36.980
But they only take
samples that you create.

00:26:36.980 --> 00:26:40.080
So we're looking for another
home for the actual field

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:42.320
samples at this point.

