are funded for five years.

00:39:34.910 --> 00:39:37.760
Well, every two-and-a-half
years, we'll put out a new CAN,

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:41.120
cooperative agreement notice,
for teams to apply to.

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:44.314
And that way, we hope
to select the new teams

00:39:44.314 --> 00:39:45.730
before the old
teams have finished

00:39:45.730 --> 00:39:47.530
their first five-year stint.

00:39:47.530 --> 00:39:49.680
That will give us
cultural continuity,

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:52.400
and the older teams
and the new teams

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:55.900
will work together better.

00:39:55.900 --> 00:39:59.110
We have the potential for
new international partners.

00:39:59.110 --> 00:40:01.860
We always hold special
sessions at major meetings

00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:04.050
like the American
Geophysical Union.

00:40:04.050 --> 00:40:06.660
This past December, we
had an all day session

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:10.030
devoted to science and
exploration topics.

00:40:10.030 --> 00:40:13.550
And we hope to continue
the significant inter-team

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:14.760
collaborations.

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:18.360
In the first year of operation,
first year, these teams

00:40:18.360 --> 00:40:22.850
have already published over
195 papers, and probably

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:25.406
400 conference papers.

00:40:25.406 --> 00:40:26.655
And this is just unbelievable.

00:40:26.655 --> 00:40:29.770
I mean anyone who's gone
through the peer review process

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:32.360
knows it takes about a
year to get something out

00:40:32.360 --> 00:40:33.740
from start to finish.

00:40:33.740 --> 00:40:35.710
And these teams
have already managed

00:40:35.710 --> 00:40:39.431
to get 195 papers through
that peer review process.

00:40:39.431 --> 00:40:41.430
So we're very proud of
them, and we look forward

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:44.210
to what they're going
to do in the future.

00:40:44.210 --> 00:40:46.730
One thing that we thought you
guys might like to hear about,

00:40:46.730 --> 00:40:49.760
lessons learned
from our experience

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:50.965
with virtual collaborations.

00:40:50.965 --> 00:40:53.090
I haven't talked to you
very much about what we use

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:53.990
or how we do it.

00:40:53.990 --> 00:40:56.180
I've got the slides if
you want to know more.

00:40:56.180 --> 00:40:58.080
But we use Adobe Connect.

00:40:58.080 --> 00:41:01.590
And we found that that
serves our purposes best.

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:03.340
There are many ways
that we could do this,

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:05.430
but that is one
that works for us.

00:41:05.430 --> 00:41:08.340
And so, what we've
learned over the years

00:41:08.340 --> 00:41:10.420
is that it's really
important to conduct

00:41:10.420 --> 00:41:16.130
personal one-on-one training
before we have anybody present.

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:19.297
It's important to
provide a checklist

00:41:19.297 --> 00:41:21.630
so that even though they think
they're familiar with how

00:41:21.630 --> 00:41:23.580
to turn on their camera
and set things up,

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:25.580
they've got a little
checklist they can go down.

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:27.980
That saves a lot of
time and trouble.

00:41:27.980 --> 00:41:30.760
Test, configure, and
optimize the off-site video

00:41:30.760 --> 00:41:33.225
teleconferencing system.

00:41:33.225 --> 00:41:35.130
This is critical.

00:41:35.130 --> 00:41:39.940
We provide a technical
producer and a host MC speaker

00:41:39.940 --> 00:41:43.820
who's familiar with what
virtual communications are like.

00:41:43.820 --> 00:41:46.410
And that means that when
there's some awkward pause,

00:41:46.410 --> 00:41:50.050
or some time, or something isn't
sounding quite right, that MC

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:53.320
knows the right thing to say,
the way to keep everybody

00:41:53.320 --> 00:41:56.212
engaged, and the way to
get us through the problem.

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:01.719
We like to have redundant
systems and backup roles

00:42:01.719 --> 00:42:03.510
so that there isn't a
single point failure.

00:42:03.510 --> 00:42:06.110
That's something we've learned
from NASA and the Apollo

00:42:06.110 --> 00:42:07.780
Program.

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:10.320
What experience has taught us.

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:13.280
Create an environment
that's inviting and has

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:14.620
a real natural feel.

00:42:14.620 --> 00:42:18.010
Designate a facilitator
for each event.

00:42:18.010 --> 00:42:22.300
Use social media and
dedicated online discussion

00:42:22.300 --> 00:42:26.240
to involve and engage the online
audience and the participants,

00:42:26.240 --> 00:42:27.884
as well as the speaker.

00:42:27.884 --> 00:42:30.050
And that's why we like Adobe
Connect, because you've

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:32.300
got that little chat box,
that window where people

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:34.117
can type in their questions.

00:42:34.117 --> 00:42:35.700
And sometimes you
see people answering

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:37.930
each other's questions
in the chat box,

00:42:37.930 --> 00:42:40.680
while the speaker just continues
on with their presentation.

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:43.450
Now as a speaker, I find
that really disconcerting.

00:42:43.450 --> 00:42:45.424
I don't like looking
at that chat box.

00:42:45.424 --> 00:42:46.840
If somebody's
asking a question, I

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:50.490
want to be the one answering
it, not having somebody else.

00:42:50.490 --> 00:42:53.550
But it turns out a lot of
other people feel differently.

00:42:53.550 --> 00:42:55.120
They love having that chat box.

00:42:55.120 --> 00:42:57.990
And so, they really use it,
and they go to town with it.

00:42:57.990 --> 00:43:01.950
And I have to admit,
it's value added.

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:04.550
And let's see, just
try to accommodate

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:06.140
time zones, that's obvious.

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.320
Ninety-minute
sessions work best.

00:43:08.320 --> 00:43:10.530
We try and follow those
with a 10-minute break.

00:43:10.530 --> 00:43:12.340
And have no more than
three sessions a day,

00:43:12.340 --> 00:43:15.200
or you're going to
lose your audience.

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:19.760
And in conclusion, I
think the main takeaways

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:23.280
for what we've learned from
the virtual institute model

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:26.380
is that by having longer
periods of funding--

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:29.800
the five-year funding--
that's long for a scientists

00:43:29.800 --> 00:43:33.090
because usually they have to
write proposals for one or two,

00:43:33.090 --> 00:43:34.280
maybe three years.

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:37.760
And by giving them a larger
amount of funding-- the teams

00:43:37.760 --> 00:43:40.450
each get roughly
$1.2 million a year.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:44.950
And this enables them to
then support their students.

00:43:44.950 --> 00:43:46.860
You can support a
student for five years

00:43:46.860 --> 00:43:49.300
and get them all the way
through graduate school,

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:51.430
if they start at the right time.

00:43:51.430 --> 00:43:54.700
But by doing this we get
unexpected discoveries

00:43:54.700 --> 00:43:59.070
from the interdisciplinary
and inter-team collaboration

00:43:59.070 --> 00:44:00.970
that comes about
through this research.

00:44:00.970 --> 00:44:04.670
So the whole really is more
than the sum of the parts.

00:44:04.670 --> 00:44:07.610
And we see incredible
productivity from these teams.

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:10.780
So we know that the taxpayer,
all of you, all of us,

00:44:10.780 --> 00:44:13.340
are getting a lot of
bang for you buck.

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:16.430
The ability to assemble the
best possible team regardless

00:44:16.430 --> 00:44:18.570
of where they're
geographically located,

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:21.140
and the cost savings
that you get, obviously,

00:44:21.140 --> 00:44:23.180
by not having to
travel everywhere,

00:44:23.180 --> 00:44:26.300
both in time and
energy, really, I think,

00:44:26.300 --> 00:44:28.430
gets that productivity up.

00:44:28.430 --> 00:44:30.430
And the long-term
stability for the students,

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:33.740
our future workforce, this
is so important to all of us.

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:36.970
So with that, I think
that's everything I brought.

00:44:36.970 --> 00:44:40.200
And I'm happy to
answer any questions.

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:43.200
And we've got, of course,
Brian Day and Brad Bailey

00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:46.360
here as well that are also
happy to take your questions.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:48.590
AUDIENCE: Is NASA the
first organization

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:51.090
to try this virtual institute?

00:44:51.090 --> 00:44:54.052
I thought it would have
been very popular by now.

00:44:54.052 --> 00:44:56.010
YVONNE PENDLETON: Well,
that's a good question.

00:44:56.010 --> 00:44:58.140
The National Science
Foundation actually

00:44:58.140 --> 00:44:59.780
has tried this as well.

00:44:59.780 --> 00:45:02.300
I think their model is
slightly different from ours.

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:05.010
But I do believe
NASA was the first.

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:08.740
And I think with the NASA
Astrobiology Institute,

00:45:08.740 --> 00:45:12.640
they have the longest running
history, from 1998 to now.

00:45:12.640 --> 00:45:14.140
And they are going strong.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:17.490
So we took a lot of our
cues from what the NAI did.

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:22.970
And I think the NSF, it
probably learned a bit

00:45:22.970 --> 00:45:25.640
from what NASA did as well.

00:45:25.640 --> 00:45:28.220
But I don't know of
other organizations.

00:45:28.220 --> 00:45:31.760
I can tell you that both the
Office of Management and Budget

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:34.610
and the White House had been
interested in what we're doing.

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:36.300
And just about a
month or two ago,

00:45:36.300 --> 00:45:38.452
they asked me to get them
a presentation as well,

00:45:38.452 --> 00:45:40.160
because they're looking
at how this might

00:45:40.160 --> 00:45:42.410
apply to other
government agencies.

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:46.470
So you might see more virtual
institutes in the future.

00:45:46.470 --> 00:45:49.950
AUDIENCE: So what's the
typical collaboration schedule

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:51.910
for many of these
collaborations.

00:45:51.910 --> 00:45:54.720
Do they all get together
like weekly or monthly,

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:59.550
or is it just like the PIs,
or is it the whole ecosystem?

00:45:59.550 --> 00:46:02.050
YVONNE PENDLETON:
That's a great question.

00:46:02.050 --> 00:46:06.161
So the question, it could
be answered differently

00:46:06.161 --> 00:46:07.160
for the different teams.

00:46:07.160 --> 00:46:09.610
They are allowed to
set their own schedule

00:46:09.610 --> 00:46:11.990
and do what works best for them.

00:46:11.990 --> 00:46:14.470
But I know some
teams that have--

00:46:14.470 --> 00:46:16.844
almost all teams have at
least a monthly meeting,

00:46:16.844 --> 00:46:18.260
in addition to the
monthly meeting

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:20.780
that they have with us
at the central office.

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:22.860
All the PIs get
together and report

00:46:22.860 --> 00:46:24.970
on what their teams have
been doing once a month.

00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:27.590
But within their team, they
do at least once a month,

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:29.720
some of them on a weekly basis.

00:46:29.720 --> 00:46:33.320
And I think it really depends
on whether their people are all

00:46:33.320 --> 00:46:36.180
co-located in one place, or
whether they're spread out

00:46:36.180 --> 00:46:39.720
and they need to tag up
with them around there.

00:46:39.720 --> 00:46:41.240
But one of the
things that we think

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:44.320
is very important in running
the virtual institute

00:46:44.320 --> 00:46:47.970
is not to over constrain
what the teams do.

00:46:47.970 --> 00:46:50.860
As a scientist myself,
I know that I really

00:46:50.860 --> 00:46:54.260
appreciate the leadership
getting the obstacles out

00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:56.340
of the way and letting
me get my job done.

00:46:56.340 --> 00:46:59.110
And that's what we're trying
to do with the teams as well.

00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:01.360
So when they have new
directions, new ideas that they

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:03.220
want to go down, they
don't have to check in

00:47:03.220 --> 00:47:05.360
with us every
minute of every day.

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:07.260
If it's a major
redirect, we'd like

00:47:07.260 --> 00:47:09.550
them to talk to
us about it first.

00:47:09.550 --> 00:47:12.610
But in general,
if all they do is

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:14.340
what they wrote
in their proposal,

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:15.780
we would be disappointed.

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:18.250
Because we know that new
science, and new creativity,

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:21.860
and new ideas come
at the intersection

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:22.970
of many disciplines.

00:47:22.970 --> 00:47:25.010
And those clever
ideas that they get

00:47:25.010 --> 00:47:29.110
by having these weekly
or monthly discussions,

00:47:29.110 --> 00:47:32.640
however often they
want to do it.

00:47:32.640 --> 00:47:36.110
AUDIENCE: So I know a
lot of other NASA groups

00:47:36.110 --> 00:47:39.120
still insist on
face-to-face meetings.

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:43.700
Many of the Cassini, things
like that, all that groups

00:47:43.700 --> 00:47:45.070
meet together.

00:47:45.070 --> 00:47:50.530
Do you think you could
give advice face to them as

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:53.550
to whether such-- everybody
needs to get together

00:47:53.550 --> 00:47:55.470
in the same room
is still necessary.

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:58.220
Or do you think those
face-to-face meetings still

00:47:58.220 --> 00:47:58.840
have a place?

00:47:58.840 --> 00:48:00.299
Or do you think
this is the future?

00:48:00.299 --> 00:48:02.340
YVONNE PENDLETON: Sure,
a very important message.

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:03.840
I'm so glad you
asked that question.

00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:06.700
Because a very important
message to take away here also

00:48:06.700 --> 00:48:09.360
is that virtual is
not always the answer.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:12.320
And there are some
really important reasons

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:15.510
and situations where you want
to have that face-to-face.

00:48:15.510 --> 00:48:20.010
And I know from the
team activities,

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:22.410
my husband, who is also
a planetary scientist,

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:23.910
has been on several teams.

00:48:23.910 --> 00:48:26.675
And I've watched
what they have to do

00:48:26.675 --> 00:48:28.300
and the way that they
have to interact.

00:48:28.300 --> 00:48:29.758
And right now
they're getting ready

00:48:29.758 --> 00:48:31.780
for the Pluto
encounter that's going

00:48:31.780 --> 00:48:34.680
to happen in July, July 15th.

00:48:34.680 --> 00:48:38.660
They're meeting on a regular
basis in person, every month,

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:41.701
or every three to four weeks,
maybe even more frequent.

00:48:41.701 --> 00:48:42.200
Yeah.

00:48:42.200 --> 00:48:43.990
See OK, you're
part of that maybe?

00:48:43.990 --> 00:48:47.174
OK, and so that's critical.

00:48:47.174 --> 00:48:47.840
That's critical.

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:49.880
And we are not by
any means suggesting

00:48:49.880 --> 00:48:52.590
that this replace
those critical times.

00:48:52.590 --> 00:48:54.200
But there are plenty
of other times

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:56.640
where we find that
virtual does work great.

00:48:56.640 --> 00:48:58.860
And people ought to
be open minded to it

00:48:58.860 --> 00:48:59.970
and give it a chance.

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:02.990
Also, I think the problem is
that when they think virtual,

00:49:02.990 --> 00:49:05.800
they might think of some
bad experience they had

00:49:05.800 --> 00:49:08.530
where the audio was
poor, the video was poor,

00:49:08.530 --> 00:49:11.490
you wasted a lot of time
trying to get people set up.

00:49:11.490 --> 00:49:13.110
That is not what we do.

00:49:13.110 --> 00:49:17.200
Come and watch one of our
video archived sessions,

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:19.882
or join us for something, and
you'll see the difference.

00:49:19.882 --> 00:49:21.590
And part of that
difference is because we

00:49:21.590 --> 00:49:24.820
have a technical staff
in the central office

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:28.860
that provides the bridging among
whatever platform you choose

00:49:28.860 --> 00:49:32.700
to join in by, or the practicing
with the presenters ahead

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:33.760
of time.

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:36.070
They try to debug it,
so that to the audience

00:49:36.070 --> 00:49:37.300
it really looks flawless.

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:40.930
And the audio quality is high,
and the video quality is high.

00:49:40.930 --> 00:49:42.410
And your experience
is much better.

00:49:42.410 --> 00:49:44.320
Your frustration
level goes way down.

00:49:44.320 --> 00:49:47.570
So there are some cases where
it works exceedingly well,

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:49.280
and other places
where I wouldn't

00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:51.527
try to replace the
old fashioned way.

00:49:51.527 --> 00:49:52.610
FEMALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:49:52.610 --> 00:49:54.550
Well, thank you
very much Yvonne.

00:49:54.550 --> 00:49:55.716
YVONNE PENDLETON: Thank you.

00:49:55.716 --> 00:49:57.600
It's a pleasure to be here.

